text: *They could have made a great movie with an honest effort to portray the man and his life as it really was* but instead they filmed popcorn fare geared towards an adolescent audience. ( _Dragon: The Bruce Lee Story_ is also 99% fantasy) The real Bruce Lee did fight a man who crashed one of his classes and challenged him to a fight. Bruce made the challenger wait till he was done teaching the class and then proceeded to put his shit out in the street in well under 60 seconds. The entire class witnessed it (including Kareem Abdul Jabar!) and the fight was described as anything but cinematic, ending with Bruce smashing his fists into the back of his opponents head as the loser ran for his life. Best Part was that Bruce later accepted the man who challenged him as his own student. He didn't hold grudges. That was the real Bruce Lee.

text: This movie is disrespectful to Bruce Lee. He might not have been a humble guy, but the actor portrays a very insecure character. He was a true mixed martial artist, and if you read his book Tao of Jeet Kun Do, he explains that his technique is efficient and affective. As usual Hollywood whitewashes the protagonist to make a white man the focus of this movie. Linda Lee isnt all mentioned here and the plot is focused around a fight that had no witnesses. For anyone who doesn't know bruce lee and is watching this movie, please do some good research to get a better understanding of who he was. The Chinese were very upset for him teaching non-chinese and women Kung Fu and there was a possibility he was poisoned for breaking barriers, no way he died of an asprin allergy.

text: If I had the money, the influence and the recognition as a director, I would make a film on the life of Bruce Lee, given the permission of his late wife of course. It would be made nothing like this film what so ever, I am afraid to say without any form of disrespect, it is absolutely awful.  To make a bio of such a legend and add traditional Kung fu film fighting sequences-Where the hero beats up 10 plus baddies-is quite frankly very poor.  Yes Bruce added some traditional Chinese movie artistic moves in his early films which were highly unrealistic, but they were early days, his becoming a recognized actor in that field. Later he choreographed actual real life fighting techniques into his film sequences.   Portraying an actor taking on multiple people in a film is one thing, depicting a Bio of Bruce doing  it in real life to make a film is another, he never. I find it an insult to him that a movie maker would portray him in this way.  If your going to make a film, a bio, of his life, then start at the beginning. Make a real life story of his life, not just a film where you can make money of the back of a name, which is all these films have ever done since his death.  There is a beautiful story to be told, as said if I had the money I would tell it, in its true entirety.
